FPP - Ch. 8 Exercises

ARIMA Models
Dan Hong | dnaeye@gmail.com

The following are my answers to the exercises in the excellent book Forecasting: Principles & Practice by Rob J Hyndman and George Athanasopoulos.

1. Figure 8.31 shows the ACFs for 36 random numbers, 360 random numbers and 1,000 random numbers.

1a. Explain the differences among these figures. Do they all indicate that the data are white noise?

Based on the ACF plots, the left two datasets have some significant autocorrelation (e.g., lag 12 in the 1st plot; lags 2 and 6 in the 2nd plot), but most are within the blue lines of significance.

1b. Why are the critical values at different distances from the mean of zero? Why are the autocorrelations different in each figure when they each refer to white noise?

Because white noise is random, autocorrelations are also random and can happen at different lags of varying degrees.

2. A classic example of a non-stationary series is the daily closing IBM stock price series (data set ibmclose). Use R to plot the daily closing prices for IBM stock and the ACF and PACF. Explain how each plot shows that the series is non-stationary and should be differenced.

tsdisplay(ibmclose)

The data points in the regular time-series plot appear to be a random walk, which implies that each point is highly correlated with the previous point.

The ACF plot shows significant and very large autocorrelation at every lag.

The PACF plot shows only significant autocorrelation at the 1st lag, which is expected, as it is actually itself (see Ch. 8.5). This indicates that even first-order differencing will make the data stationary (i.e., white noise).

3a. usnetelec

6. Use R to simulate and plot some data from simple ARIMA models.

6a. Use the following R code to generate data from an AR(1) model with \(\phi_t = 0.6\) and \(\sigma^2 = 1\). The process starts with \(y_1 = 0.\)

y_0.6 <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100)
for(i in 2:100)
  y_0.6[i] <- 0.6*y_0.6[i-1] + e[i]

6b. Produce a time plot for the series. How does the plot change as you change \(\phi_1\)?

y_1.0 <- ts(numeric(100))
for(i in 2:100)
  y_1.0[i] <- 1.0*y_1.0[i-1] + e[i]
y_0.2 <- ts(numeric(100))
for(i in 2:100)
  y_0.2[i] <- 0.2*y_0.2[i-1] + e[i]
autoplot(y_0.6) + autolayer(y_1.0) + autolayer(y_0.2)

As \(\phi\) becomes smaller, the peaks and troughs in the plot generally become less extreme. On the other hand, as it gets larger, the more extreme they get.

6c. Write your own code to generate data from an MA(1) model with \(\phi_1 = 0.6\) and \(\sigma^2\) = 1.

set.seed(123)
y <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
for(i in 2:100) {
  y[i] <- 3 + e[i] + 0.6*e[i-1]
}

6d. Produce a time plot for the series. How does the plot change as you change \(\theta_1\)?

autoplot(y)

set.seed(123)
y_0.9 <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
for(i in 2:100) {
  y_0.9[i] <- 3 + e[i] + 0.9*e[i-1]
}
autoplot(y_0.9)

With a larger \(\theta\) - 0.9 - the pattern appears roughly the same, but the shape of some of the peaks and troughs are different. A few short peaks/troughs became more gradual, while others became more sharp.

set.seed(123)
y_0.3 <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
for(i in 2:100) {
  y_0.3[i] <- 3 + e[i] + 0.3*e[i-1]
}
autoplot(y_0.3)

Lowering \(\theta\) to 0.3 appeared to have done the same.

6e. Generate data from an ARMA(1,1) model with \(\phi_1\) = 0.6, \(\theta_1\) = 0.6, and \(\sigma^2\) = 1.

set.seed(123)
y_arma1 <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
for(i in 2:100) {
  y_arma1[i] <- 0.6*y[i] + e[i] + 0.6*e[i-1]
}
autoplot(y_arma1)

The pattern has stayed roughly the same, but now some of the data points are negative.

6f. Generate data from an AR(2) model with \(\phi_1\) = -0.8, \(\phi_2\) = 0.3, and \(\sigma^2\) = 1. (Note that these parameters will give a non-stationary series.)

set.seed(123)
y_ar2 <- ts(numeric(100))
e <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
for(i in 3:100){
  y_ar2[i] <- -0.8*y_ar2[i-1] + 0.3*y_ar2[i-2] + e[i]
}
autoplot(y_ar2)

This AR(2) model interestingly has a very distinct pattern, regularly oscillating between positive and negative regions with increasing variance.

6g. Graph the latter two series and compare them.

As shown above, the ARMA(1) plot has a random, stationary pattern, while the AR(2) model exhibits a clear, non-stationary one.

7. Consider wmurders, the number of women murdered each year (per 100,000 standard population) in the United States.

7a. By studying appropriate graphs of the series in R, find an appropriate ARIMA(\(p, d, q\)) model for these data.

autoplot(wmurders)

The time series does not appear to be stationary, so it needs to be differenced to make it so.

wmurders_diff <- diff(wmurders)
autoplot(wmurders_diff)

There seems to be a negative trend in the differenced time series, so itll need to be differenced again.

wmurders_diff2 <- diff(wmurders, differences=2)
autoplot(wmurders_diff2)

The second-order differenced time series now appears stationary enough for further analysis.

ggtsdisplay(wmurders_diff2)

Although the lags in the ACF oscillate between negative and positive regions, the magnitude of these lags appear to be gradually getting smaller after lag 2, which would indicate a AR(1) model (since we should ignore lag 1 in an ACF plot).

The PACF also tails off gradually, but in a different manner, with only 1 significant lag, indicating an MA(1) model.

So, the best model would be an ARIMA(1,2,1) model.

Arima(wmurders, order=c(1,2,1))
Series: wmurders 
ARIMA(1,2,1) 

Coefficients:
          ar1      ma1
      -0.2434  -0.8261
s.e.   0.1553   0.1143

sigma^2 estimated as 0.04632:  log likelihood=6.44
AIC=-6.88   AICc=-6.39   BIC=-0.97

7b. Should you include a constant in the model? Explain.

No, because when \(d\) > 1, including a constant would introduce a quadratic or higher order trend that is dangerous when forecasting. See the section on Arima() in Rob Hyndmans Hyndsight Blog.

7c. Write this model in terms of the backshift operator.

\((1-\phi_1B)(1-B)^2y_t = (1+\theta_1B)\epsilon_t\)

See Ch. 8.2 for backshift notation and Ch. 8.5 for non-seasonal ARIMA models.

7d. Fit the model using R and examine the residuals. Is the model satisfactory?

fit <- Arima(wmurders, order=c(1,2,1))
checkresiduals(fit)

    Ljung-Box test

data:  Residuals from ARIMA(1,2,1)
Q* = 12.419, df = 8, p-value = 0.1335

Model df: 2.   Total lags used: 10

The ACF shows no significant lags among the residuals, which appear to be mostly normally distributed. Furthermore, the Ljung-Box test returned a large (i.e., greater than 0.05) p-value of 0.1335, so the time series is likely white noise.

When comparing the RMSE between the different models, several are practically tied at about 0.186, but the simplest model is often the best, which would be the one the auto.arima function found, which was ARIMA(2,1,0). The ACF plot showed only one significant spike at lag 12, and the residual distribution was fairly normal.

The ETS model forecasts a slight dampening over time, which is not what the general positive trend in the historical data suggests. In addition, its RMSE of 0.1984366 is worse than the 0.1859861 of the ARIMA(2,1,0) model.

10. Consider austourists, the quarterly number of international tourists to Australia for the period 19992010.

10a. Describe the time plot.

autoplot(austourists)

The time series has a positive trend that is seasonal with increasing variance.

10b. What can you learn from the ACF graph?

ggAcf(austourists)

There is definitely autocorrelation and high seasonality.

10c. What can you learn from the PACF graph?

ggPacf(austourists)

There are spikes at lag 4 and 8, also suggesting seasonality.

10d. Produce plots of the seasonally differenced data \((1-B^4)Y_t\). What model do these graphs suggest?

ggtsdisplay(diff(austourists, lag=4))
